The first-year anatomy examination was held in Hall B, which seated three hundred and twenty students in rows so close together that the person behind you could read your answers without leaning forward.

The answer sheets were distributed fifteen minutes before the examination started. They were light yellow, carbon-smudged at the bottom right corner where the roll numbers were printed, and they smelled of the duplicating ink that the college administration had been using since at least the previous decade.

Vicky picked up his sheet from the stack passed along the row, wrote his roll number at the top, and began.

He wrote for three hours.

He did not look up from the paper during those three hours, which was why he didn't notice the sheet next to him had been stacked the wrong way and his roll number was printed on someone else's booklet, and someone else's roll number was printed on his. The smudging had been significant. The number 7 and the number 1 had a particular way of looking similar when the carbon had run.

He submitted the paper. The student in row seven, seat four — a young man named Devendra Rao — submitted what appeared to be a blank sheet, because it was.

---

They were both called to the principal's office the next morning.

Devendra Rao arrived first and had been sitting in the left chair for eleven minutes when Vicky came in. Devendra was the kind of student who had never, in his twelve years of formal education, been called to any principal's office for any reason. He sat in the chair with the rigid posture of someone who is attempting to indicate, through body language alone, that he is fundamentally not that kind of person.

Professor Iyer, the principal, was a small man with reading glasses worn on the end of his nose, which he had to tilt his chin up to see through. He looked at the two answer sheets side by side on his desk. He looked at Vicky. He looked at Devendra. He looked at the sheets again.

"In thirty-one years," Iyer said slowly, "I have not seen this specific problem before."

Nobody said anything.

"The sheet with your handwriting," he said to Vicky, "has this boy's roll number on it." He indicated Devendra. "The blank sheet has your roll number. You cannot both fail and you cannot both pass on the basis of the same answers."

"He studied," Devendra said. His voice came out more urgent than he had intended. "I've seen him study. He studies every day. I've seen the light under his door."

Iyer looked at Devendra with the expression of a man who appreciates loyalty and is simultaneously confused by its relevance. He turned to Vicky. "And you? What do you say?"

Vicky looked at the blank sheet with his number on it. Then at the filled sheet with Devendra's number. Then at Iyer.

"I say I should have checked the roll number," he said. "And that I am sorry for the inconvenience to this gentleman." He nodded toward Devendra, who was still sitting with extreme posture.

Iyer took his glasses off and cleaned them with his handkerchief, which he did whenever he was making a decision that the rulebook had not entirely anticipated. He cleaned them for a long time.

"Both of you pass," he said finally. "Neither of you will discuss this. With anyone. Under any circumstances whatsoever."

He put his glasses back on.

"Understood?"

"Understood," said Vicky.

"Understood," said Devendra, in the tone of someone who has just been told they survived something they didn't know they were in danger of.

---

Outside the principal's office, in the corridor with the broken fluorescent light that had been blinking since October, Devendra turned to Vicky.

"How did you do on the paper?" he asked.

"Okay," Vicky said.

Devendra nodded. He opened his textbook. He began walking toward the library.

He never mentioned the examination to Vicky again, and Vicky never mentioned it to him. They were not friends after this, precisely, but in the years of college that remained, whenever they happened to pass each other in a corridor or a canteen, there was a specific quality to the silence between them — the silence of two people who once stood in a principal's office together and both survived, which is a different thing from friendship but not entirely unlike it.

---

Adarsh heard about it from the class representative, who had been told by the invigilator, who had been told to keep it quiet.

He found Vicky in the room that afternoon, reading. "I heard about the exam."

"It was a clerical error," Vicky said, without looking up.

"You both passed."

"Yes."

"Because of the light under your door," Adarsh said.

Vicky looked up.

"The other boy told the principal he'd seen you studying. That you study every day. That's why Iyer passed you both."

Vicky was quiet for a moment. He looked at the ceiling. "I don't know that boy's name," he said.

"Devendra Rao," Adarsh said. "Room twelve, ground floor."

Vicky nodded. He turned back to his book. He read for a moment, then closed it. "I should return a favour to him at some point," he said.

He never found the right occasion to do it. Devendra Rao left college two years later to pursue civil services and passed on his third attempt, which had nothing to do with Vicky, but Vicky told Adarsh about it when he read it in a newspaper years later, as if it had.

